Based on my search results, I found relevant information about using `createSetNameAction`, `executeTransaction`, and `lockedAccess` in Premiere Pro UXP. Here's what I found:

## Key Concepts

The `executeTransaction` method executes an undoable transaction by passing a compound action, with an optional undo string parameter. The `lockedAccess` method gets a read/upgrade locked access to the Project, ensuring the project state will not change during the execution of the callback function.(no content)You can call `executeTransaction` while having locked access.

## createSetNameAction

The `createSetNameAction(inName: string)` method returns an action that renames a projectItem.(no content)For track items, `createSetNameAction(inName: string)` returns an action that renames the trackItem.

## Example Code

Here's a working example pattern from the Adobe community that demonstrates how to use these methods together:

```javascript
const app = require("premierepro");

async function renameItem() {
    try {
        const project = await app.Project.getActiveProject();
        const rootItem = await project.getRootItem();
        const items = await rootItem.getItems();

        // Find the item you want to rename
        let itemToRename;
        for (let i = 0; i < items.length; i++) {
            if (items[i].name == "OldName.MOV") {
                itemToRename = items[i];
                break;
            }
        }

        // Create & Execute the Rename Action
        project.lockedAccess(() => {
            project.executeTransaction((compoundAction) => {
                const renameAction = itemToRename.createSetNameAction("NewName");
                compoundAction.addAction(renameAction);
            }, "Rename Item"); // Optional undo string
        });
    } catch (err) {
        console.error(err);
    }
}
```

`lockedAccess` and `executeTransaction` are essential for making actions work properly - users have reported that using these methods together "did the trick" for executing actions like `createAddMarkerAction`.

## Additional Notes

An important difference between ExtendScript (and CEP) and UXP in Premiere is that all ExtendScript calls to Premiere were synchronous, meaning they blocked the Premiere UI while executing. In UXP, a method call is asynchronous and does not block the UI thread.(no content)As of August 2025, only Premiere Pro BETA builds support UXP plugins.

For more examples and documentation, you can check the official [Adobe UXP Premiere Pro samples repository](https://github.com/AdobeDocs/uxp-premiere-pro-samples) and the [official API documentation](https://developer.adobe.com/premiere-pro/uxp/).


